LinkedIn (longer)
I was building a backend and ran into a gap: Swagger UI was not supported in my stack, so I could not get clean, first-class docs for routes and request/response bodies. Instead of hacking around it, I built the missing layer into this project.

The approach: route annotations carry metadata (method, path, summary, tags), request bodies, and responses. A scanner reads those annotations and outputs a standard OpenAPI JSON file, and Swagger UI renders the docs by pointing at that JSON.

What I learned building this:
- Annotations are just classes with const constructors
- The analyzer reads annotation values as compile-time constants
- A small scanner can build OpenAPI JSON without build_runner
- Swagger UI is simply HTML + a JSON spec
- Good schema structure makes client generation reliable
- Documentation is part of product quality

This project reinforced something simple: making APIs usable is just as important as making them work.

